postcontent:
For sale is a Lewis Machine and Tool Co. complete upper receiver with 16in .300 Blackout/whisper barrel! 

LMT makes some of the best assault rifles in the world. This particular upper receiver comes with a full auto bolt carrier assembly/bolt, a magpul fore grip, Magpul flip battle sights, and a .300 Blackout/Whisper barrel that has been BARELY broken in at around 100 rounds. 

This upper receiver fits on to any military spec AR15 lower receiver and the .300 Blackout round uses the same magazines as the standard .223/5.56 assault rifle round. 

The MRP upper features two locking bolts that when removed, allow the operator to simply pull off the barrel and replace it with any LMT MRP barrel such as .223/5.56, .204 Ruger or the 6.8 SPC round. All of the mentioned calibers use the same bolt/carrier and magazines. To lock the barrel back into place you simply tighten the locking bolts to the appropriate strength using the included torque wrench.

The upper itself is in great condition and was only used as a range rifle. Shell deflector is testimony to how gently used it is.

Email for more pics/questions!

title: For Sale:  WW1 Scovill Model 1907 M Artillery Shell Inert 75 mm
postcontent:
WW1 1907m Artillery Shell
"21-seconds" timefuze nose, which the gunner would "set" for the specific time-of-flight from the cannon to the intended target. That type of timefuze was used primarily in what were known as "Shrapnel" shells... meaning, in addition to an explosive powder-charge they contained many dozens of lead antipersonnel balls. Almost a primitive smart bomb.
75mm case has some trench art, one looks like a woman holding an American flag. Other I cannot make out.
About 2 feet long and almost 15 pounds.
Properly de-militarized and inert.
A very rare piece of history

title: For Sale/Trade:  Browning Crazy Horse Commemorative Shadow Box Obsidian Knife
postcontent:
Hello, this is a shadow box made by Browning commemorating Sioux Warrior Chief "Crazy Horse" Condition of the contents is mint, there are some scratches/dings on the outside of the box. It's large in size measuring 30"x9"x3" and is surprisingly heavy. No shipping at this time because of the fragility of the item. There were only 500 boxes made and 1847 obsidian knives made. Here is a a little more info:

"Tashunka Witko," Oglala Lakota Sioux Warrior. Crazy Horse was born around 1845 on the Republican River that traces the Nebraska-Kansas border. He was raised with tribal traditions of generosity, courage and self-denial. He ordered the attack on Lt. Col. George A. Custer's Seventh Cavalry and never surrendered the lands claimed by his people. When asked where were his lands, he replied, "My lands are where my dead lie buried."

The Crazy Horse knife sports a handle made of wood from a grove of aspen trees, which grew on the sacred Pine Ridge Reservation land in southern Nebraska. The Aspen is revered by the Sioux Nation as the "Tree of Life." The 4 1/2" x 1 1/2" blade is made from knapped obsidian, a hard volcanic glass. Its color is variegated rust black and is affixed to the hilt with leather strips. Horsehair tassels dangle from brass cones, threaded with bone beads lashed to the leather binding. Four brass tacks represent the four seasons. The fringed buckskin sheath is brain-tanned, hand-made and beaded with a familiar Sioux pattern.

http://www.browning.com/products/catalog/knives/detail-historic.asp?fid=029G&cid=321&tid=005&bg=x
